            <class name="tests.LoginTest"/> <!-- can add more classes indipendently (package name + . + class  name) --> 
        </classes>
    </test>
</suite> 


<!--
================================================================================
TESTNG XML PARAMETERS (3rd way of parameterized/data-driven testing)
================================================================================

Purpose:
Pass values from testng.xml into test methods at runtime.

Mental Model:
Instead of hardcoding values in Java or reading them from an Excel/CSV file,
TestNG can read values from this XML file and automatically inject them into
the test method using the @Parameters annotation.

Flow:
testng.xml
        ↓
<parameter name="browser" value="chrome"/>
        ↓
@Parameters({"browser"})
        ↓
public void test(String browser)

TestNG automatically passes the value ("chrome") into the browser parameter.

================================================================================
WHEN SHOULD I USE THIS?
================================================================================

Best for SUITE CONFIGURATION (configuration shared by the entire test suite):

• Browser (Chrome, Firefox, Edge)
• Environment (QA, UAT, Staging, Production)
• Base URL
• Username / Password
• API endpoint
• Timeout values
• Feature flags
• Any configuration that may change between test runs

Example:

Run #1
browser = chrome
environment = QA

Run #2
browser = firefox
environment = UAT

The same test code runs, but with different configuration values.

================================================================================
WHEN SHOULD I NOT USE THIS?
================================================================================

Not ideal for large data-driven testing.

Example:
100 login usernames/passwords
50 search keywords
200 customer records

For multiple rows of test data, use:

✔ TestNG @DataProvider
✔ Excel / CSV / JSON
✔ Database

These are much easier to maintain for large datasets.

================================================================================
COMPARISON OF THE 3 METHODS
================================================================================

1. @DataProvider (hardcoded)
- Small datasets
- Fast to write
- Test data lives inside Java code

2. Excel / CSV / JSON
- Real data-driven testing
- Large datasets
- Easy for testers/business users to update without changing code

3. TestNG XML Parameters
- Configuration-driven testing
- Passes suite-level configuration values
- Common for browser, environment, URL, credentials, etc.

================================================================================
INTERVIEW SUMMARY
================================================================================

DataProvider = multiple test cases.
Excel/CSV = external test data.
TestNG XML Parameters = suite-level configuration values.

A common real-world setup:
- TestNG XML chooses the browser/environment.
- DataProvider or Excel supplies the actual test data.
================================================================================
-->